body_text.text:
For thin or nonobese dogs, the dorsal iliac crest is a popular location because it is readily accessible (Fig. 2
). In small dogs and cats with a thin dorsal ilial crest, transilial samples for core samples are preferred over parallel placement of the needle within the ilium (Fig. 3
). Patients may be positioned in sternal or lateral recumbency for ilial samples. The needle is introduced at the widest part of the dorsal ilium and directed ventromedial to conform to the concavity of the pelvic bone. If placed too laterally, the biopsy instrument may enter only cortical bone or slip off the sides into surrounding muscle or adipose tissue.
